description:
## Severity
Critical
## Dimension
security
## Location
src/tools/bash/mod.rs:62-103
## Violation
`cmd.spawn()` (line 72 windows / line 84 unix) is invoked BEFORE the capacity guard at lines 87-101. The capacity check is performed only after the child process already exists in the OS, defeating the purpose of `MAX_BACKGROUND_SHELLS`. A flood of `run_in_background=true` calls will spawn unbounded children before any of them are rejected — the rejection only prevents tracking, not spawning.

Quoted source (mod.rs:75-103):
```
        #[cfg(not(windows))]
        let child = {
            let mut cmd = Command::new("bash");
            cmd.args(["-c", command])
                .current_dir(&cwd)
                .stdout(Stdio::piped())
                .stderr(Stdio::piped())
                .process_group(0);
            apply_env_scrub(&mut cmd);
            cmd.spawn()
        };

        // Enforce maximum shell limit BEFORE spawning the process
        if let Ok(mut shells) = self.shells.lock() {
            ...
            if shells.len() >= MAX_BACKGROUND_SHELLS {
                return Err(...);
            }
        }

        let mut child = child.map_err(...)?;
```

The comment lies — the spawn already happened on line 72/84. The orphan child is leaked because we return `Err` before the spawn result is bound.
## Mandated refactor
1. Move the capacity check above the `let child = { ... cmd.spawn() }` block so the spawn never happens when at capacity.
2. Hold the `shells` lock across both the check AND the insert to make the cap atomic with respect to concurrent spawners.
3. Add a regression test that fires `MAX_BACKGROUND_SHELLS+1` concurrent spawns and asserts the OS process count does not exceed the cap.
